At the Zhejiang University Academic Annual Conference, students took center stage, and their research findings were truly mind-blowing – Xinhua News Agency
Washing hands with air, determining diseases by exhaling, and precisely identifying the sources of smog—these were some of the innovative academic achievements recognized at the opening ceremony of Zhejiang University’s 2016 Annual Academic Conference last night.
The main researchers behind these achievements are all students. Their research covers a wide range of fields, including the environment, mechanics, energy, medicine, life sciences, and humanities education. Starting from a simple, curious idea, the students have created many high-end inventions with practical value. Some of these projects have won awards both domestically and internationally.
Bio-sensors: Your personal health check-up doctors
The team led by Dr. Zhang Diming from the School of Biomedical Engineering demonstrated a biosensor for use on smartphones. The sensor is only half the size of a typical smartphone.
“All you need to do is take a gentle breath, and this device will be able to preliminarily assess your health status based on the components of the air you exhale.”
Zhang Diming explained that this set of sensors is connected to a smartphone, and after exhaling, a health report will be displayed on the phone.
Smart wristbands available on the market that can detect health conditions generally measure physical parameters such as temperature and pulse.
This set of biosensors utilizes graphene, a novel material, and its target is chemical elements. The sensors’ keen “sense of smell” enables them to provide a more in-depth and accurate reflection of the body’s health status.
Intelligent surgical lights: The doctor’s high-powered “eyes”
In addition to smartphones, smart surgical lights are also being used in operating rooms.
This invention won the silver award at the 44th International Invention Exhibition in Geneva, Switzerland, this year.
The teams of Master's students Zhu Linjing and Shen Junfei from the School of Optoelectronic Science and Engineering have identified shortcomings in traditional surgical lights and developed a new concept, resulting in the invention of an intelligent LED surgical shadowless lamp.
“The inadequate early detection and removal of many diseases are related to the lighting used in doctors’ operating rooms.”
Shen Junfei said that, for example, during the early detection of cancer, if doctors cannot clearly see all the tumor tissues in a timely manner, the cancer cells may continue to spread later on.
This intelligent surgical lamp features four light discs that adjust the spectrum to enhance the contrast between different tissues when illuminated.
During the surgical procedure, the doctor can adjust the size of the light spot, the brightness level, the spectrum, the color uniformity, and the shadow-free rate at any time, according to the surgical requirements and the individual patient’s preferences.
This intelligent surgical lighting system has already been tested in hospitals such as Sir Run Run Shaw Hospital affiliated with Zhejiang University School of Medicine and Children’s Hospital affiliated with Zhejiang University School of Medicine, and has received positive feedback.
Last October, this invention won the first prize in the National Challenge Cup.
Washing your hands with air: it saves water and looks cool too!
Ordinary people just wash their hands by running water over them, at most using some soap or hand sanitizer. However, students like Li Qizhang have invented a “handwashing device that uses air”.
As long as we stand on the sink of the device, our weight will compress the air and force it out.
“It’s just like a pump.”
The compressed air forms a fluid at the faucet and mixes with the water.
In this way, we can wash our hands thoroughly!
Color reaction and bacterial residue tests have proven that the effectiveness of handwashing using this method is the same as that of conventional handwashing methods.
This device relies solely on the force of gravity to operate, ensuring thorough cleaning while saving 90% of the water used. The entire process is completely energy-free, making it both environmentally friendly and efficient.
Last year, at the second Global Major Challenges Summit, this invention stood out among many of the world’s top universities and won the only gold award.
