Educational Commentary: What is needed to rescue abducted children?
If we draw an analogy with the famous public service advertisement slogan “No buying, no selling; no killing,” then in an environment where there is no demand for child kidnapping, through collective prevention and public opposition to such crimes, trafficking activities would become unprofitable, high-risk, and costly. As a result, such crimes would not occur so frequently.
Recently, an emergency information release platform for missing children, developed by the Anti-Abduction Office of the Criminal Investigation Bureau of the Ministry of Public Security, was launched.
This is an internet information platform created to establish an authoritative channel for releasing information about missing children and to help locate abducted children in a timely manner.
Hearing that the app is called “Reunion,” it immediately feels very warm and comforting.
The new technological methods are not only named in a way that evokes a sense of “artistry” and emotion, but they also make proper use of information technology, making them practical and effective.
The primary goal of anti-trafficking law enforcement is to recover the abducted children and ensure their personal safety and freedom.
Secondly comes the trial and punishment of the suspect.
The significance of criminal punishment can be discussed in various aspects, ranging from individual punishment and social prevention to legal education. There are many important concepts that can be mentioned in this context.
However, before the trafficking case is solved, priority should be given to ensuring the personal safety of the victims.
We need to prioritize matters based on their urgency. Under the pressing goal of “searching for and rescuing,” topics that are highly controversial and have varying opinions, such as whether child trafficking should always be punishable by death, can be set aside for more cautious discussion. However, the rescue of abducted children cannot wait.
Based on the experience in investigating such cases, human traffickers tend to leave the crime scene as soon as possible after they have achieved their goal.
With every additional minute wasted in the search for a kidnapped child, the child moves further away from their parents, and the difficulty of solving the case increases accordingly.
In this situation, taking effective measures such as the “Reunification” platform, which directly contribute to solving the case and finding the child, is indeed a pragmatic approach.
After all, “combating trafficking” is a major task that requires the entire legal system to be put in operation in order to be effectively carried out.
To combat crime and protect the rights of children and parents, it is essential to implement a comprehensive approach that includes improvements in legislation, judicial safeguards, and meticulous law enforcement. All these efforts must be guided by the principle of caring for the vulnerable and supporting those in need.
Furthermore, the prevention of child trafficking can be improved further, from the family level to society as a whole.
For example, in a common scenario, a family of three is resting at the train station. The parents are fast asleep, and when they wake up, they realize that their child is missing.
You can’t expect a two-year-old child to have sufficient self-protection skills, but as the parent of such a young child, you should at least have a decent level of awareness about how to protect them.
It is the most basic measure to prevent children from being abducted: either parents take turns resting, or the children are placed in a safe and secure environment under protection.
From another perspective of the police’s efforts to combat trafficking crimes, the side that purchases abducted children should also be addressed and punished.
A single illegal act is often just one link in a much longer chain of events.
According to the provisions of our country's Criminal Law, the minimum penalty for the crime of trafficking in children is 5 years in prison; in particularly serious cases, the punishment can be death, accompanied by the confiscation of property.
With a high threshold for prosecution and severe maximum penalties, the crime of trafficking children clearly falls under those that are subject to more stringent punishment, amidst the general trend towards lighter sanctions.
Yet, to this day, a considerable number of cases of abduction and trafficking still occur every year.
It is evident that some people have outdated views on raising children and a weak sense of legal awareness.
The legal education for this group of people should be provided in parallel.
To effectively control the crime of trafficking, we cannot rely solely on strict law enforcement by the authorities.
If the “market” for child kidnapping is widespread, and kidnappers are driven by greed and constantly innovate their methods of abduction, leading to a sort of “battle of wits” with law enforcement, then efforts to combat kidnapping are bound to become inefficient and ineffective.
Therefore, breaking down outdated concepts and promoting legal knowledge can also help to effectively eradicate the crimes of child trafficking and purchase.
Yang Haodong delivered a speech on the spirit of the Sixth Plenary Session of the 19th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China and the Provincial Party Congress at Malanshan.
Draw strength for progress from the party’s century-long history of struggle
Hunan Daily, December 10th (All-media reporter: Gong Baiwei) According to the unified arrangements of the Provincial Party Committee, on the morning of December 10th, Yang Haodong, a member of the Standing Committee of the Provincial Party Committee and the head of the Provincial Party Committee’s Publicity Department, delivered an interactive lecture at the Malanshan Video and Cultural Innovation Park. The lecture focused on thoroughly studying and implementing the spirit of the Sixth Plenary Session of the 19th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China, as well as the important speeches, instructions, and directives of General Secretary
Yang Haodong explained the core essence and practical requirements of the plenary session's spirit in a clear, comprehensive, and systematic manner from three aspects: ideals and beliefs, as well as the original mission; self-revolution and the role of the Party as a youthful force; and the Party's leadership and theories. He did so by combining his own insights and personal experiences.
He pointed out that it is necessary to study the spirit of the plenary session in conjunction with General Secretary Xi Jinping’s important speeches, instructions, and directives regarding Hunan, as well as the spirit of the provincial party congress. By integrating these elements, we can enhance our ideological, political, and practical awareness of upholding the “two establishments” and achieving the “two maintenances,” and resolutely move forward in the direction guided by General Secretary Xi Jinping.
During the interactive session, representatives of grassroots officials, enterprises, and young people posed questions regarding the relationship between the three historical resolutions, how to understand the decisive significance of the “Two Establishments,” how cultural enterprises should set their direction, and how young people in the new era can draw strength from the Party’s century-long history. Yang Haodong answered these questions in simple language and with vivid examples. He earnestly encouraged young Party members to draw inspiration for progress from the Party’s century of struggle, to unite closely around the Central Committee, to follow the Party unwaveringly, and to use their youth to fulfill their responsibilities and
The number of college graduates in the Beijing area is expected to reach 268,000 in 2022 – Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, December 11 (Reporter Yang Na) The reporter learned from a recent video conference on employment and entrepreneurship for Beijing college graduates held jointly by the Beijing Municipal Education Commission and the Beijing Municipal Human Resources and Social Security Bureau that the number of college graduates in Beijing is expected to reach 268,000 in 2022, an increase of 16,000 compared to last year.
A relevant official from the Beijing Municipal Human Resources and Social Security Bureau stated that efforts will be made to promote the employment of Beijing university graduates in various areas, including enhancing the matching of supply and demand, strengthening policy support, expanding employment opportunities, ensuring assistance for those in need, supporting innovation and entrepreneurship, and improving the efficiency of services.
