I want to give tennis a try, but I’m afraid I won’t be able to stick with it, so I’m looking for a racket at a reasonable price to get started with.
Unfriendly, indeed. In fact, the price is often directly proportional to the level of friendliness of a product or service. If you can’t tell the difference, it’s generally the case that more expensive options will be less friendly than cheaper ones. These so-called “entry-level” products are actually just industrial waste.
They have very low strength; when the ball hits the racket, the vibration is extremely intense. Hard balls can’t withstand this, and even experienced players find it difficult to control them.
The logic and underlying message behind this are as follows: Tennis is such a difficult sport; we knew you wouldn’t be able to learn it, and we also knew you wouldn’t be willing to spend a lot of money on a good racket. So we came up with a cheap one to deceive you. After playing with it a couple of times, you’ll probably stop playing altogether. Since the racket is cheap, you won’t feel too bad about it.
When you’re really able to tell the difference between good and bad things, it’ll mean you’ve made progress. Then you can come to me and buy the expensive ones—I’ll make money twice over.
I suggest spending a similar amount of money on a used, higher-quality racket. Consider brands like Prince or Dunlop; these are not very well-known, so even good rackets from these brands don’t command high prices. A new racket can cost around 500–600 yuan, while a used one can be found for 200 yuan. Wouldn’t it be great to enjoy the performance of a racket that costs thousands of yuan, but at a fraction of the price?
It’s quite friendly to beginners, but becomes useless once they’ve passed the beginner stage. However, most people, especially women, don’t manage to make it past that beginner phase.
