Xinhua All Media + | Beijing Youth Ice Hockey League Fuels the Passion for the Winter Olympics - Xinhua News Agency
On December 11th, Pang Yaotian (center), a player from the Beijing DreamING team, took a shot during the match.
On that day, the 2021-2022 Beijing Youth Ice Hockey Club League continued to compete at various ice rinks in Beijing.
This league season is divided into a regular competition and a playoff phase, with participants ranging in age from U6 to U18. The teams are categorized into a competitive group and a selection group, attracting nearly 3,600 players from 256 representative teams across the city.
After more than a decade of development, the Beijing Youth Ice Hockey Club League has become a platform for young ice hockey enthusiasts in Beijing to exchange skills and make new friends. It also serves as a source of talented players for the city's youth ice hockey teams.
The league competitions have played a significant role in promoting ice hockey among young people in Beijing, fueling the enthusiasm for ice hockey during the Winter Olympics and laying the foundation for the development of ice hockey in Beijing in the post-Olympic period.
Girl acts as a target for arrows to raise money for her sister: “It’s still bearable when I think it’s just a superficial injury” – Xinhua News Agency
In Hangzhou’s Wulin Square, a girl stood in front of a large wooden board that read, “Human target; ten yuan per arrow.”
Yesterday morning, a photo showing a girl from Hangzhou willingly acting as a “target” to raise funds for her sister went viral on social media.
The photo shows a girl in Hangzhou’s Wulin Square standing in front of a large wooden board that is slightly taller than her. On the board is written “Human target, ten yuan per arrow,” indicating that passersby can use a bow and arrow to shoot the target after making a payment.
This behavior has sparked a heated discussion among netizens.
Last night, the person in charge of publicity at the Xiacheng Branch of the Hangzhou Public Security Bureau confirmed to a reporter from The Beijing News that the police had indeed confirmed that the girl was collecting donations for her sister, which led to such an extreme reaction. However, such behavior is not advisable. After being reprimanded, the girl left the local police station yesterday.
Girl used as “target” on the street to raise funds; the defendant was warned
In the picture circulating online, a girl with long hair is standing in a “V” shape in front of a large wooden board. On the board, the words “Human target; 10 yuan per arrow” are written in black ink. On another wooden board in front of her, her bank account number, as well as her WeChat and Alipay account information, are listed.
The image sparked controversy after it was uploaded to the internet.
Some netizens believe that this action is a form of “attention-seeking begging,” while many others express sympathy for the individuals involved.
“We discovered this situation around 10 a.m. on the 23rd while patrolling near the square; there were already quite a number of onlookers at that time.”
Police officers from the Tianshui Police Station, located near the incident site, said in an interview with local media that there were two girls setting up stalls, both around 20 years old and dressed in a youthful and attractive manner.
Among them, the girl who was used as a “human target” kept crying and begged passersby to play the game with her; another girl helped by shouting that her friend’s sister had leukemia and urgently needed money for surgery, asking everyone for their help.
“We contacted the local police in Guizhou and learned that the girl was raising funds for her sister’s leukemia treatment.”
Last night, the person in charge of publicity at the Xiacheng Branch of the Hangzhou Public Security Bureau told a reporter from The Beijing News that the girl’s name is Jijiali, and she was collecting donations for her sister Jijiayan.
However, since the treatment still costs over 300,000 yuan, and no good way to raise the funds has been thought of immediately, such an action was taken.
He said that throughout the entire process, one of the two girls served as a target, while the other acted as an assistant but did not actually participate in the activity. No one was observed shooting arrows; instead, people just watched and took photos, which were then posted on Weibo.
Subsequently, the police, with the assistance of the public security department, determined that the bow and arrows used did not fall under the category of items subject to regulation.
The person in charge stated, “This type of attention-grabbing fundraising method is not advocated.”
After being warned by the police officers at the police station, she has left the station.
