What was the biggest hit in 2021?
There’s no doubt it’s the Tokyo Olympics.
Do you think only Olympic athletes can win awards?
Some time ago, an article titled “Look! Project Managers Can Compete in Olympic Events for Gold Medals” became very popular. It mentioned that project managers can definitely take the lead in many projects, with no one being able to match them: carrying heavy loads, traveling on business, staying up late are all part of their daily routine, and stepping in to fix problems, taking the blame, and apologizing are just second nature to them.
An article that seems like a joke or mockery actually reveals the daily hardships faced by project managers, reflecting the sense of powerlessness in current project management practices.
And those engaged in project management also gradually begin to take certain actions in order to get out of the difficulties they face at work.
Judging from the increasing number of applicants for the PMP (Project Management Professional) certification each year, it is evident that more and more professionals in project management are improving their skills through learning.
According to the “China Project Management: Twenty Years of Development Report (1999-2019)”, as of September 2019, the total number of people who had registered for the PMP® exam nationwide approached 600,000, approximately 420,000 of them obtained the PMP® certification, and around 300,000 held valid certifications, accounting for 31.2% of the global total number of PMP® certified individuals.
In the past decade, the number of PMP (Project Management Professional) certification holders has been increasing year by year. This indicates that more and more project managers are realizing that relying solely on traditional methods and past “experiences” is no longer effective. The rapidly changing work environment teaches us that we must learn from the achievements of scientific pioneers and build upon their knowledge to find new ways forward.
However, does obtaining the PMP certification guarantee that project management work will go smoothly without any obstacles?
Many beginners in project management say that by studying courses related to PMP/IPMP, they can systematically grasp the key concepts in the ten areas and five process groups of project management. However, when it comes to actually carrying out project management tasks, they still find themselves completely confused.
Many project managers often report the following issues: - A lack of proper understanding of project management principles; relying solely on personal experience, possessing only theoretical knowledge without knowing how to apply it in practice. - The absence of a systematic project management process and support framework, making it difficult to implement strategies effectively in work. As a result, project estimates are inaccurate, control mechanisms are ineffective, and projects are constantly delayed. - Unclear division of responsibilities among team members, and those with more experience don’t know how to handle certain situations appropriately. - Inefficient cross-departmental communication, which hinders the progress of projects.
Therefore, having focused on product innovation and research and development (R&D) management for over a decade, Zhongtian Huaxia Consulting has helped numerous outstanding companies cultivate a large number of key R&D talents such as product managers and project managers. The company has also received honorary titles such as “Demonstration Base for R&D Management Talent Training in Chinese Enterprises.” Now, Zhongtian Huaxia Consulting is bringing the online course “Special Training Camp for R&D Project Managers” to you.
“R&D Project Manager Training Camp” Online Course: This is an online, fragmented learning approach that combines practical cases, tools, and methods from numerous R&D-oriented companies to help you acquire the essential knowledge and standard procedures required for project management, paving your way towards advanced skills in this field.
This is also an opportunity for companies to promote the training of project managers at a lower cost and with less investment, thereby achieving more efficient operational results.
Words alone don’t carry much weight; it’s better to see what other students have to say about this course. This course is not only developed by the expert team from Zhongtian Huaxia (formerly part of Huawei’s R&D management team) but also incorporates advanced international project management methodologies and real business scenarios from numerous well-known companies, providing a clear and professional explanation of the content.
It will also provide scientific and practical management tools and methods, as well as a wealth of template forms, to help learners apply what they have learned to their actual work after the course.
