Vietnam People’s Daily Online – The Gulf Cooperation Council responds to common challenges
The stops on the itinerary of Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman include Oman, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar, Bahrain, and Kuwait.
It is worth noting that this is the first visit by Crown Prince Mohammed to Qatar since the embargo imposed on the country by Saudi Arabia and its Arab allies in mid-2017, which led to a diplomatic crisis in the Gulf region.
During this crisis, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, and Egypt severed their diplomatic relations with Qatar and imposed a comprehensive embargo on it, accusing Qatar of supporting terrorist organizations and having close ties with Iran.
Diplomatic tensions have severely impacted the internal cohesion of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) and had a negative effect on the economies of the countries in the region.
Four Arab countries have blocked land, sea, and air routes leading to Qatar.
The crisis was only resolved at the Gulf Cooperation Council summit in January 2021, when the Gulf states signed an agreement facilitated by the United States and Kuwait, aiming for “unity and stability.”
Saudi Arabia has reopened its border with Qatar.
Saudi Arabia and Egypt are taking the lead in efforts to restore relations with Qatar, having appointed new ambassadors in that country.
The Gulf Arab countries have resolved their differences in order to restore relations with Qatar, driven by the need to unite for the interests of all nations and regional stability, as well as to address common challenges.
During the visit of the Saudi Crown Prince to Oman, the two sides agreed to establish the first direct land route between these two Gulf neighbors.
The 725-kilometer-long corridor connecting the two countries will facilitate travel for citizens from both nations and enable the integration of their supply chains.
The Saudi Arabia Public Investment Fund (PIF) will invest $5 billion in Oman, and companies from both countries have signed 13 memorandums of understanding for cooperation worth a total of $30 billion.
The visit of the Saudi Crown Prince to the Gulf countries coincides with negotiations between Iran and major world powers aimed at saving the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPOA) regarding Iran’s nuclear program. The Gulf Arab countries have criticized this agreement, believing it fails to address the issue of Iran’s missile capabilities.
The Gulf states have always regarded Iran as a long-term “rival” and seen Iran’s nuclear program as a “threat” to regional security.
The countries of the Gulf region believe that it is flawed not to address the issue of Iran's missiles and to take no action to curb Iran's activities in the region.
Against the backdrop of failed nuclear negotiations between the major powers and Iran, which did not meet the aspirations of the Gulf countries, Saudi Arabia engaged in direct talks with Iran.
The goal is to prevent the escalation of tensions in the region.
This is one of the factors that are slowing down the economic growth of the countries in the Gulf Cooperation Council.
The upcoming Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) summit will be the first one for GCC countries since the disputes between some member states and Qatar have been resolved.
This is an opportunity for the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) to re-evaluate its diplomatic achievements in order to contribute to the restoration of GCC unity. It also presents the chance to propose measures that will enable its member states to cooperate fully in addressing common challenges and thus contribute to the stability and development of the Gulf countries.
