Claimed to have the loudest supercar exhaust sound in the New Mountain District!
The car that our team has brought for everyone this time is the dream of many men!
It is the flagship supercar from Lamborghini, the successor to the Murcielago – the Aventador LP700-4!
The price is nearly two million Malaysian ringgit, and the annual road tax is just over ten thousand Malaysian ringgit. It’s a four-wheel-drive vehicle – so why is it called the LP700?
With 700 horsepower, you can imagine how fast it would be.
Well, I don’t really know either. The data shows that the acceleration from 0 to 100 km/h only takes 2.9 seconds. That means by the time my Myvi reaches 30 km/h, the other vehicle might already be going at 100 km/h. Hmm…
The low-profile vehicle body, the imposing scissor doors, the large air inlets distributed all around the car, and the 6.5-liter V12 engine clearly visible through the glass perfectly embody the Lamborghini style.
There’s not much need to say about the car model itself; just Google it if you want more information. The editor has compiled some explanations that might not be readily available through Google searches!
It’s too much attention; wherever I go, everyone is looking at me, which makes me very uncomfortable! (Actually, it’s kind of exciting too.)
The cost of fuel for a 1-kilometer journey is around RM1 (the car owner doesn’t really care about it at all).
You should practice the proper way of getting in and out of the vehicle; otherwise, it might be a bit embarrassing (because you might not be able to climb out of the cabin and get stuck halfway).
The engine noise is so loud that you’ll go deaf as soon as you get out of the car. (But it’s still really exciting.)
The car is too large; it would be very cramped if parked in a regular parking spot. I’m really worried about getting hit by the door of the car next to me when it opens!
It’s a bit lonely because there are no competitors on the road (that’s what the editor said; it has nothing to do with the car owners, haha).
Let there be no misunderstanding: the supercar in this video is not for sale. Sorry!
Friends who want to record videos of their beloved cars are welcome to contact us!
For more car information that you don’t know, check out The Car Guide / People’s Automobile Magazine.
It involves a car accident involving a vehicle worth tens of millions of dollars!
Both the Bugatti Chiron and the Porsche 911 are well-known among car enthusiasts. The Chiron is considered one of the most expensive supercars in the world, while the price of the Porsche 911 also ranges in the millions!
A few days ago, abroad, millions of Porsche 911s and tens of millions of supercars from the Chiron series were destroyed in just a few minutes!
Looking at the results, it makes sense that the price is higher!
Let the spirit of the university resonate in harmony with the spirit of the times – Xinhua News Agency
The so-called "university spirit" refers to a series of educational philosophies and value pursuits that have been gradually established over the long term in the development of a university, representing the very essence of the institution.
From ancient times to the present, the spirit of universities has been of paramount importance for the development of politics, economics, culture, technology, society, and even the progress of a nation as a whole.
Since the birth of the world’s first modern university, universities have undertaken a unique mission that sets them apart from other social organizations. For the universities in our country, which emerged during times of national crisis, their spirit has been deeply influenced by traditional culture and the changes of the times. They promote the values of “cultivating virtue for the benefit of society” and “self-improvement leading to the governance of a peaceful nation,” as well as the patriotic commitment to “strengthening the nation through education.”
Currently, the trends of informatization and internationalization in higher education are becoming increasingly evident. The competition in education, technology, and talent on a global scale is intensifying. As an important "supply-side" component of higher education, its structural reforms are facing unprecedented opportunities and challenges.
In particular, the introduction of the "Overall Plan for Coordinating the Development of World-Class Universities and Disciplines" demonstrates China's confidence and determination in transitioning from a major country in higher education to a powerful nation in this field. It also sets even higher and more modern requirements for the development of universities.
How can we strive to become among the world’s best in a relatively short period of time, and on the basis of existing gaps, accelerate the establishment of several world-class universities and a number of world-class disciplines, thereby achieving a “overtake on a curve” strategy?
In addition to having firm confidence in their goals, the path they choose, and their own capabilities, universities should also fully leverage three key advantages: Firstly, the advantage of being a latecomer. By continuously attracting outstanding academic talents from abroad and learning from the advanced experiences of world-class universities, they can significantly improve their academic standards and the quality of education they provide. Secondly, the cultural advantage. By inheriting the wisdom accumulated over five thousand years of Chinese civilization and promoting the development of excellent traditional culture, universities can build cohesion, create a strong brand, and enhance their image. Thirdly, the institutional advantage
It is particularly important to realize that building world-class universities cannot mean that all universities should look the same. While each university should leverage its strengths, it must also showcase its unique personality and characteristics.
The distinctive features of a school should not only reflect the common Chinese characteristics but also embody each school's unique goals, educational traditions, and resource endowments.
In the case of Zhejiang University, we focus on highlighting three distinctive aspects in our educational approach: Firstly, we emphasize the cultivation of innovative and entrepreneurial talents by creating an integrated educational environment that combines science and education, as well as industry and academia, thereby forming a comprehensive ecosystem for entrepreneurship education. Secondly, we foster interdisciplinary collaboration by optimizing and adjusting the academic curriculum, establishing a supportive institutional framework for interdisciplinary research, and actively promoting the development of new interdisciplinary fields and significant research outcomes. Thirdly, we place emphasis on the role of the university in serving society by engaging in extensive international exchanges and collaborations, with the
In this process, it is particularly important to always uphold the university spirit and ensure that it resonates in harmony with the spirit of the times.
For Zhejiang University, the motto “Seeking Truth and Innovation,” the shared values of “Diligent Learning, Cultivating Virtue, Clear Discrimination, and Sincerity,” as well as the mission statement “Embracing All Rivers and Streams, Promoting Truth and Virtue, Advancing Society, and Strengthening Our Nation,” collectively constitute the latest expression of the university’s spirit.
This is an important guarantee for the school to maintain the correct direction of its educational efforts, continuously build up cultural depth, and gather spiritual strength. It is rich in meaning and has far-reaching significance.
Among these, “Haina Jianghe” (Embracing Rivers and Streams) emphasizes the spirit of openness and inclusiveness, reflecting the ambition to harness the talents of the world for its own benefit, as demonstrated by adopting the high-quality educational philosophies of renowned international institutions. “Qizhen Houde” (Promoting Truth and Virtue) highlights the pursuit of truth and goodness, suggesting that universities should not only seek knowledge but also cultivate virtue and strengthen character. “Kaiwu Qianmin” (Advancing Society and Benefiting the People) embodies the spirit of innovation and reform, encompassing both the pursuit of new
This series of spiritual concepts and value pursuits is precisely the soul of Zhejiang University’s 120-year history of education.
“The wise hear what is silent; the discerning perceive what has yet to take form.”
Chinese universities should further focus on the overall situation of the cause of socialism with Chinese characteristics, deeply understand the historical context and mission of higher education, and accelerate their development into world-class institutions.
At the same time, it is essential to uphold humanistic care and independence, allowing the spirit of academia to interact with the spirit of the times and the national ethos. This interaction will generate a continuous drive for the prosperity of the nation and the rejuvenation of the people, as well as for the realization of humanity's common ideals.
