The maximum duration for Guangxi college students to take a break from studies to start a business is 5 years – Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Nanning, May 19th (Reporter Zhang Ying) Reporters have recently learned from the Education Department of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region that in the future, colleges and universities in Guangxi will implement a flexible academic system. The duration for college students to take a break from their studies will be extended, with the period of time allowed for students to pause their studies to start a business being able to be increased by 2 to 5 years based on the original academic schedule. This time spent on taking a break to start a business can be considered as part of their practical education experience.
To promote the enhancement of entrepreneurial and innovative capabilities among college students, departments such as education and human resources in Guangxi have collaborated to establish entrepreneurial platforms. They have built more off-campus practice teaching bases for college students, university science and technology parks, college student entrepreneurship parks, and incubation centers, providing external support for their entrepreneurial endeavors.
According to the requirements, by 2020, the area of innovation and entrepreneurship practice bases in various colleges and universities should be as follows: undergraduate institutions should have bases of more than 3,000 square meters, and higher vocational schools should have bases of more than 2,000 square meters.
The government encourages universities to establish credits for innovation and entrepreneurship, and gives priority to supporting students who perform exceptionally well in innovation and entrepreneurship practices to change their majors.
University teachers are required to spend at least two months each year, every two years, working in industry or enterprises as part of their professional development, in order to enhance their awareness and capabilities in innovation and entrepreneurship education.
The Education Department of the Autonomous Region requires all universities in Guangxi to thoroughly implement the college students' innovation and entrepreneurship training program, striving to ensure that every college student participates in such a training program during their time at school.
Colleges and universities should actively organize students to participate in various innovation and entrepreneurship competitions at all levels, and provide financial support for them.
NEWS GOV-MO: The Australian University has awarded honorary doctorates to 7 distinguished individuals
The University of Macau held the “2021 Honorary Degree and Advanced Degree Award Ceremony” today (11th), conferring honorary doctorates on Liu Zunyi, Chen Kaixian, Nakamura Shuji, Li Lanjuan, Li Xiaoliang, Zhu Lilan, and Jiang Chaohui in recognition of their outstanding achievements and significant contributions to the development of society and education.
At the award ceremony, Ouyang Yu, the Chief Executive and representative of the Chancellor of the University of Macau, as well as the Secretary for Social Affairs and Culture, presented the honorary doctorate degree in the presence of Lin Jincheng, the Chairman of the University of Macau Council of Governors, and Song Yonghua, the President of the University of Macau.
Professor Liu Zunyi was awarded an Honorary Doctor of Education degree; Professor Chen Kaixian was awarded an Honorary Doctor of Science degree; Professor Nakamura Shuji was awarded an Honorary Doctor of Science degree; Professor Li Lanjuan was awarded an Honorary Doctor of Science degree; Professor Li Xiaoliang was awarded an Honorary Doctor of Business Administration degree; Professor Zhu Lilan was awarded an Honorary Doctor of Science degree; and Ms. Jiang Zhaohui was also awarded an Honorary Doctor of Science degree.
In her speech, Ouyang Yu first extended warm congratulations and high respect to the seven distinguished individuals who were awarded honorary doctorates. These individuals have achieved remarkable accomplishments in various fields and made outstanding contributions to the development of their countries and the progress of the world. Ouyang Yu also conveyed her sincere wishes to the graduates and their parents, as well as her heartfelt admiration for the university’s dedicated and highly skilled faculty members.
Sun Yifeng, a Distinguished Professor at the School of Humanities at the Australian National University, stated in her speech praising Professor Liu Zunyi that Professor Liu Zunyi is an economist renowned worldwide for his outstanding academic achievements and forward-thinking educational philosophy.
In addition to the achievements in economic development, growth, and the East Asian economic sector, he is also a visionary educational leader.
In short, he has made outstanding achievements in many fields.
When Sun Yifeng read the eulogy for Shuji Nakamura, he stated that Professor Shuji Nakamura was a pioneer in sustainable energy technology.
He became one of the three recipients of the 2014 Nobel Prize in Physics for his invention of the blue light-emitting diode (LED).
Professor Nakamura’s invention has not only completely transformed the lighting industry but also led to the development of the white light-emitting diodes (LEDs) that are now widely used in everyday life and industrial production, making a tremendous contribution to the well-being of humanity.
Sun Yifeng read out the praise for Li Lanjuan, stating that Professor Li Lanjuan, as a pioneer in the field of artificial liver technology in China, developed a unique and effective Li’s artificial liver system. This system has led to significant breakthroughs in the treatment of severe hepatitis and liver failure, significantly reducing the mortality rate associated with these conditions.
In the battle against COVID-19, the “Four Resistances and Two Balances” approach proposed by her and her team, along with the three key technologies of artificial liver, microecology, and stem cells they brought, significantly improved the survival rate of patients in critical condition.
Sun Yifeng read out the praise for Li Xiaoliang, stating that Professor Li Xiaoliang laid the foundation for innovative research in operations management, shaped the way of thinking in supply chain theory and practice, and completely transformed business models around the world.
Li Xiaoliang is known for popularizing the concept of the "whip effect" in operations management and has explored measures to address this phenomenon.
Today, in the face of the pandemic and the tense economic situation, the bullwhip effect is becoming increasingly prominent, leading to severe disruptions in the supply chain.
Li Xiaoliang’s forward-thinking research is like timely help in difficult times, assisting the industry in overcoming challenges and thereby bringing tremendous social value.
When Sun Yifeng read out the commendation from Zhu Lilan, she mentioned that in her scientific research work, she had discovered a breakthrough and innovative dyeing technique for sample preparation, which has earned her a high reputation among her peers in the scientific community both domestically and internationally.
She has been honored with significant titles such as Academician of the International Eurasian Academy of Sciences for her remarkable achievements in technology, and her brilliant accomplishments have earned her a place of respect in the world’s temple of science and technology.
Chen Xin, the acting director of the Australian Macao Chinese Medicine Research Institute, read out the tribute to Professor Chen Kaixian. He stated that Professor Chen Kaixian has been engaged in drug research and development for over 40 years. His outstanding scientific achievements, as well as his significant contributions to the country, Macao, the University of Macao, and national key laboratories, have earned him a high international reputation and prestige.
His active role in promoting the development of traditional Chinese medicine in Macau and the Greater Bay Area fully demonstrates his sense of mission in contributing to the country’s medical development strategy.
In his speech reading out the commendation from Su Chengzhong, the Dean of the Australian Institute of Technology, it was mentioned that Ms. Jiang Chaohui has been involved in the development of several significant inventions and patents, totaling more than 15 to date. These inventions are related to storage virtualization, navigation, file systems, and power management. They are all highly practical, widely used, and have enhanced the convenience of human life.
As a highly accomplished inventor, Ms. Jiang is often able to simplify complex technologies and theories, making them accessible to the general public.
Finally, Chen Kaixian read out the thank-you speech on behalf of the honorary doctors.
He is very pleased to see that the pharmaceutical industry in Macau and the Greater Bay Area has set a good example: from the establishment of the first National Key Laboratory for Traditional Chinese Medicine Quality Research at the University of Macau to the vigorous development of traditional Chinese medicine in the region, the University of Macau has played a significant role in bringing together outstanding talents in the field of traditional Chinese medicine within the Greater Bay Area.
