In September 2020, Mr. Lu learned about a factory building located in Zhangting Town, Yuyao, Zhejiang through a real estate agency. After several on-site inspections, Mr. Lu decided to purchase the factory building.
In December of the same year, after Mr. Lu discussed the details of purchasing the factory building with Mr. Lin, the family member of the property owner, he transferred 200,000 yuan via bank transfer as a deposit on the same day.
Mr. Lin signed as the recipient on the “Deposit Receipt for the Sale of the Factory Building.” The receipt states, “If the buyer does not wish to purchase the factory building, the deposit shall belong to the seller. If the seller does not wish to sell the factory building, the deposit will be returned in double to the seller. Both parties have agreed to sign the sale contract for the factory building within one week.”
However, subsequently the parties were unable to reach an agreement on key contract terms such as the scope of the factory building sale and the payment method, which led to the delay in signing the property sales contract.
Considering that the two parties failed to reach an agreement on the terms of the contract, a few days later, Mr. Lin returned the deposit of 200,000 yuan to Mr. Lu.
After much effort, Mr. Lu found a house he liked, paid the deposit, and had all the necessary funds ready to complete the purchase. All that was left was to sign the contract. However, the seller decided not to sell the property, which left Mr. Lu feeling both helpless and angry.
For this reason, Mr. Lu filed a lawsuit against Mr. Lin in the People's Court of Yuyao City.
After reviewing the case, the court held that the failure of both parties to sign a formal contract could not be solely attributed to the defendant. It was reasonably inferred that the negotiations did not succeed. Therefore, the deposit penalty rule should not apply in this case, and the defendant is not liable for the breach of contract in terms of returning the double amount of the deposit.
After the first-instance judgment, the plaintiff filed an appeal.
Recently, the appellate court upheld the original judgment.
[Lawyer’s Reminder] It is essential to exercise the necessary degree of care and diligence during the transaction process.
When signing a contract, as the buyer, it is necessary to exercise due diligence. This includes verifying information about the property owner, whether the property is occupied by anyone else, and other relevant details. The contract should also clearly specify the exact time and place of delivery to prevent any disputes that may arise during the performance of the contract.
Following the conclusion of the “Democracy Summit” on Friday, a spokesperson for China’s Ministry of Foreign Affairs stated on Saturday (December 11) that the United States’ hosting of the event was an attempt to “draw ideological lines, instrumentalize and weaponize democracy, practice anti-democratic measures under the guise of democracy, incite division and confrontation, and divert domestic tensions.”
The Chinese government believes that “for a long time, the United States has imposed its political system and values on others, promoted ‘democratic transformation,’ arbitrarily imposed unilateral sanctions, and instigated ‘color revolutions,’ resulting in catastrophic consequences.”
“Democracy” has long become a “massive weapon of destruction” for the United States to use in its interference with other countries.
This summit is an action taken by Biden to fulfill his campaign promises.
The two-day conference was conducted via video, and leaders from 111 countries around the world were invited to attend, including those from Taiwan. However, China and Russia were not invited.
On the eve of the summit, China and Russia criticized the United States for the problems in its own democracy, stating that the US did not have the qualifications to host such a gathering.
There are also skeptical voices both internationally and within the United States. For example, it has been criticized that some of the leaders invited to attend the summit have authoritarian tendencies, such as those from the Philippines, Poland, and Brazil. Some suspect that the true intention of the Biden administration in organizing this summit was not to promote democracy but rather to serve geopolitical interests.
The newly appointed German Chancellor, Olaf Scholz, also participated in the Video Democracy Summit.
A statement issued by China’s Ministry of Foreign Affairs on Saturday stated, “Today, the pathologies of American democracy are fully exposed. Issues such as money politics, identity politics, party antagonisms, political polarization, social divisions, racial tensions, and wealth disparity are intensifying.” It added that American democracy is a “rich people’s game” built on the foundation of capitalism.
U.S. President Joe Biden stated in his speech, “As leaders of the government, it is our responsibility to listen to our citizens, strengthen the safeguards of democracy, promote reforms, and achieve transparent and accountable governance. This will help us better withstand the forces of authoritarianism and those who seek power at the expense of the public interest.”
He emphasized that democracy is not something to be taken for granted. “We must constantly renew it with each new generation, and in my view, this is the decisive challenge of our time.”
Biden also said that global democracy and human rights "face persistent and concerning challenges, and democracy needs defenders to uphold them."
The United States has pledged that following this Democracy Summit, a one-year initiative will be launched. This initiative includes a fund of $424.4 million aimed at strengthening democracy around the world and providing support to independent news media.
The United States hopes that all countries will make specific and public commitments to improve their democratic systems before the physical Democracy Summit scheduled for the end of 2022.
Biden said, “Let’s make sure all our countries fulfill their commitments and report on the progress we’ve made next year.”
