In Sabah, 3,200 newborn babies did not receive their birth certificates due to a shortage of specially designed anti-counterfeiting paper.
(Kuching, November 11) The Sabah National Registration Office stated that due to the exhaustion of stock of special anti-counterfeiting paper, birth registration certificates have not been issued for newborn babies since early October. To date, a total of 3,200 people have been affected by this situation.
However, the director of the bureau, Keruaminus, assured that all the babies for whom birth registration papers have been applied for have their information already recorded in the system, and the papers will be issued upon arrival next week.
At the press conference, he responded to a report by an online media outlet regarding issues with the printing of newspaper paper in Sabah that had persisted for up to 10 months.
He said that the issues had arisen two months ago, and Sarawak was also facing the same problems.
“One of the reasons is that Chinese manufacturers producing the special anti-counterfeiting paper have been affected by the pandemic, which has led to delays in their delivery to our country.”
He explained that the anti-counterfeiting paper used in Sabah’s newspaper production is different from that used in other regions, and therefore it is not possible to borrow stock from other states.
Keruaminus revealed that the latest batch of anti-counterfeiting paper arrived in Kuala Lumpur on the 6th of this month and was then handed over to the printing company on the 8th for partial printing.
“The office will send someone to Kuala Lumpur next Thursday to collect the goods. Upon returning to Sabah, the final printing steps will be carried out immediately. It is estimated that the goods can be delivered to the applicants by December 20, which is about two more working days.”
“We will inform the applicants to go to the local branches to collect the birth registration forms.”
He added that Sabah has issued a total of 24,801 birth registration papers so far this year.
