Don’t scare people into collapsing at the starting line – Xinhua News Agency
When visiting book fairs, it's often possible to sense the popularity of books on success and self-improvement.
Many of the current success books promote the “best-of-principles” approach – that is, they assume or imply from the start that you have the ability to achieve something, and only then tell you what you need to do in order to do so.
In other words, it’s as if we’re skipping right over the most important and fundamental step: “how to do it.”
For this very reason, these books all share a common characteristic: either you go all in and do your best, or you don’t do anything at all; it’s either 100% or 0%; either you climb Mount Tai, or you just stay put.
This “best principle,” which anyone looking at it would have to admit is absolutely correct, will scare 99% of people away before they even get a chance to start.
Because this theory promotes the idea of “you need to make a firm decision to turn over a new leaf and undergo a complete 180-degree transformation,” and this is precisely what many people’s greatest weakness is.
For those who are rigid, conservative, and resistant to change, trying to shout in their ears “You need to change” is undoubtedly self-deceiving and like talking to a stone.
The vast majority of people become hesitant in the face of the word “change,” hesitate to take action, and struggle to make up their minds. Alternatively, some may make a hasty decision to change on a whim and bravely take the first step, but such progress often doesn’t last long; they give up after a short while, failing to maintain consistency.
Mr. Ma Sanli’s famous cross-talk performance “Starting from Tomorrow” is a classic example that vividly illustrates this “universal human nature.”
The biggest problem with the “Best Principle” is that the threshold for achieving it is too high; it often exceeds the capabilities of ordinary people, leaving the vast majority of them feeling discouraged and unable to proceed.
Perhaps the “second-best principle” is the approach that has the greatest potential for helping more ordinary people on their way to relative success.
The core of the “second-best principle” lies in “lowering the threshold” – it encourages the idea of accumulating small victories to achieve a greater one. In other words, if you can’t achieve 100%, it’s still okay to achieve 1%, because 1 is always greater than 0. If you can’t climb Mount Tai, it’s sufficient to climb the small hill in front of your house; after all, that’s better than staying put.
In short, as long as you do something, it’s always better than not doing anything at all.
With the threshold being significantly lowered, there are more possibilities for ordinary people to persevere. And whenever one persists in something, the chances of success also increase.
It’s just that the path to success by following the “second-best principle” is a bit longer.
In summary, although the “best principle” ostensibly aims to help everyone succeed, it ultimately motivates only a minority of people. It is the “second-best principle” that can effectively motivate a larger number of individuals and bring benefits to as many people as possible.
