Let’s take a look at some of the [strange trending searches] today.
What is considered normal public opinion?
Randomly select three trending topics: “The Dragon Raising Festival on February 2nd,” “The price increase of Good Luck Friends (a snack brand),” and the “Houlala incident.” Public opinion around these topics peaks, followed by a “decrease in the index” (shown as a smooth curve), before eventually subsiding. If secondary public opinion reactions arise, small spikes may reappear.
They look exactly the same as the [Online Public Opinion Evolution Model] that was previously displayed on the official website of the Cyberspace Administration of China.
What is abnormal public opinion?
Randomly select six trending searches from the same event, and present them in the forms of “isolated peak,” “zigzag,” and “cliff.”
“Island Peak” pattern: Artificially boosted to quickly rise on the trending lists, attracting public attention; “Sawtooth” pattern: Periodic boosts to ensure the topic remains on the trending list; “Cliff” pattern: A collective decline; once the trend has fulfilled its purpose, it moves on to a new task or “battlefield.”
In Figure 9, the peak of one event’s popularity coincides precisely with the trough of another event, down to the very second. This must indicate that a group of coordinated “water army” (internet trolls or botnets) has received a command to launch a new round of attacks.
The专业化 of black public relations is evident in this case: dozens of trending searches make it onto the list simultaneously. These searches are strategically designed to either attract attention, disseminate scientific knowledge, stir up controversy, divert attention, influence perception, mislead judgment, manipulate emotions, or influence decision-making. The accounts belonging to these black propaganda networks operate in a meticulous and phased manner, taking into account almost every aspect of how public opinion spreads.
Communication is a science. By setting aside all subjective factors such as opinions and emotions, and focusing solely on objective data, even black PR (negative public relations efforts) will have no place to hide.
Wherever one has walked, traces are left behind; let’s dig them out together.
Data source: The Hot Search Time Machine.
Countries such as Mauritius have reported their first cases of Omicron virus infections – Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, December 12 – According to reports from Xinhua correspondents abroad, Mauritius, Cyprus, and Malawi have recently reported their first cases of infection with the Omicron variant of the COVID-19 virus.
Mauritius reported its first two cases of the Omicron variant on the 10th.
According to Minister of Health Kailesh Jagutpal, one of the infected individuals was a tourist who departed from South Africa and arrived in Mauritius on November 27; the other infected person is a local resident of Mauritius who tested positive for the virus on November 30 after coming into contact with someone who had recently traveled to South Africa and then returned.
After being isolated and treated in the hospital, the nucleic acid test results for both of these infected individuals turned negative, and they have now returned to their respective residences.
On the 10th, the Cyprus Ministry of Health announced that the country had detected its first three cases of infection with the Omicron variant.
All three of these people are students who returned from abroad at the beginning of this month. Since their symptoms were mild, they did not need to be hospitalized for treatment.
To prevent the spread of the Omicron variant, the Serbian government has been continuously intensifying its prevention and control measures.
From December 6th to January 10th of next year, all passengers over the age of 12 entering the country by plane will be required to undergo a nucleic acid test at the airport at their own expense upon arrival.
On the 10th, the Serbian Ministry of Health also announced that it would begin vaccinating children aged 5 to 11 in the country with the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine.
On the 9th, Malawi's Health Minister, Kunbize Chiponda, announced that the country had detected its first three cases of infection with the Omicron variant.
The country’s health department conducted genomic sequencing on 12 COVID-19 positive samples collected between November 9 and December 2, and identified these three cases of infection.
