Starry Sky Appointment | The Geminid Meteor Shower will reach its peak on the 14th – Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Tianjin, December 12 (Reporter Zhou Runjian) According to astronomy experts, the Geminid meteor shower, one of the three major meteor showers in the Northern Hemisphere and also the last large-scale meteor shower of the year, will reach its peak on December 14. Friends who enjoy watching meteor showers can observe it in the latter half of the night on that day.
An astronomy enthusiast from Beijing, An Jiu, captured the Geminid meteor shower on December 13, 2018, in Qinghai.
The parent bodies of most meteor showers are periodic comets, but the parent body of the Geminid meteor shower is asteroid 3200 Phaethon, which is an Apollo-type asteroid.
The Geminid meteor shower is also the second known meteor shower that is not originated by a comet.
Xiu Lipeng, a member of the Tianjin Astronomical Society and an expert in popularizing astronomy, explained that, just like the blockbuster New Year’s movies, the Geminid meteor shower usually occurs at the end of the year, with its “screening period” lasting from December 4th to December 17th.
This meteor shower is known for its high and steady rate of meteors. Along with the Quadrantid meteor shower and the Perseid meteor shower, it is considered one of the three major meteor showers in the Northern Hemisphere.
A notable feature of the Geminid meteor shower is the relatively slow speed of the meteoroids, as well as their rich range of colors and the presence of many fireballs. This makes it an excellent option for both amateur stargazers and beginners in astrophotography.
Yang Jing, an astronomy enthusiast from Tianjin, photographed the Geminid meteor shower on December 13, 2020, in Jizhou, Tianjin.
Astronomical forecasts indicate that this year’s Geminid meteor shower will reach its peak around 15:00 on December 14th, with a ZHR (Zenith Hourly Rate) of 150. The ZHR represents the number of meteors visible per hour under ideal observation conditions, when the radiant point of the shower is directly above the observer’s head.
Gemini Meteor Shower Recommendation Index Chart.
“Last year, the Geminid meteor shower, known for its beautiful displays of falling stars, left a deep impression on people. However, this year’s Geminid shower will be affected by moonlight, which may reduce the intensity of the show somewhat.”
The 14th falls on the 11th day of the 11th lunar month, which is a waxing gibbous moon phase. The bright moonlight can interfere with observations. Fortunately, the moon will set in the second half of the night, and at that time, the radiant point of the Geminid meteor shower will also be higher in the sky.
Friends who enjoy meteor showers can observe them in the hours after the moon sets in the latter half of the night, but be sure to keep warm to avoid catching a cold.
How can one observe as many meteors as possible?
“It is not recommended to conduct observations in urban areas. You can choose a location in the suburbs or countryside that is at a high altitude, has minimal light pollution, and offers a clear view in the northeast direction. Then, wait patiently for the moon to set before conducting the visual observation.”
It’s important to note that the Geminid meteor shower has a high rate of meteors coming from various directions, so there’s no need to constantly focus on the radiant point of the shower during observation.
Friends who enjoy photography and want to capture stunning ‘meteor shower’ photos should opt for a wide-angle lens with a large aperture. Use a high ISO setting and the maximum aperture when taking the shots.
Considering stability and durability, a tripod, spare batteries, and a remote control for the shutter are also essential.
Xiu Lipeng reminded them.
What are the differences in market positioning between laser TVs and traditional TVs?
As I understand it, the traditional TV mentioned by the questioner should refer to LCD TVs. The main differences in market positioning between laser TVs and LCD TVs are as follows:
Firstly, laser TVs are more focused on the large-screen market.
Compared to the market positioning of LCD TVs, which are widely available, laser TVs seem to focus more on the large-screen market. In other words, laser TVs are essentially products designed for large screens.
Currently, the sizes of mainstream LCD TVs range from 55 to 65 inches, while laser TVs generally have a size of 75 inches or more, with the largest models exceeding 100 inches, fully meeting users' demand for large-screen color TVs.
In recent years, the shipment and sales volume of laser TVs have been continuously increasing globally, accounting for over 60% of the total TV sales in the 80-inch and larger size category.
According to the predictions of CICAC, in 2020, the sales volume of laser TVs is expected to grow by more than 140%, continuing to maintain a high growth rate.
The reason for such outstanding success in the large-screen market is mainly due to the excellent eye-care features of laser TVs.
Based on the principle of diffuse reflection in laser TVs, the light emitted by the laser source does not directly enter the eyes. Compared to the backlight of liquid crystal TVs, this imaging process is more similar to how objects are perceived under natural conditions, resulting in less irritation to the eyes.
Experts from the CCSTC Saisi Laboratory and the Ophthalmology Department of Peking Union Medical College Hospital conducted a rigorous comparative study in which participants viewed both laser TVs and LCD TVs under the same conditions, resulting in 144 sets of test data.
The data confirms that laser TVs indeed have strong eye-protecting properties and can even have a positive effect in certain aspects.
In an era where attention to visual health is increasing, laser TVs are not only attracting more and more users due to their benefits for eye care but also opening up a new breakthrough in the color TV market.
Secondly, laser TVs are more targeted at the high-end market.
Contrary to the continuous decline in the prices of LCD TVs, the prices of laser TVs currently available on the market are mostly over 10,000 yuan. As the size and light source of these TVs improve, their prices are gradually increasing.
Why are laser TVs so expensive?
There must be some logic to it.
With the continuous advancement of light sources and technological levels, laser TVs possess many advantages that liquid crystal TVs and projectors are unable to achieve.
Thanks to their ultra-short-throw projection technology, laser TVs require a much shorter projection distance compared to traditional projectors. This allows for a 100-inch large-screen experience at a close range, requiring minimal space. Additionally, the main unit of the laser TV is compact and takes up very little room.
In terms of brightness, high-brand laser TVs can achieve luminosities of over 2000 lumens.
Furthermore, with lower heat generation, there is less wear and tear on the equipment, resulting in a longer lifespan for the television.
In addition to this, many high-end laser TV models feature true 4K ultra-high-definition resolution, artificial intelligence systems, bionic screens, and numerous other cutting-edge technologies, providing users with an even more stunning visual and auditory experience.
It’s not so much a case of “fake demand” as rather the result of a more detailed segmentation of market needs. In terms of image quality and cost-effectiveness, laser TVs are not the right choice for audio-visual enthusiasts. If you want to combine a large screen with a comfortable viewing environment but face limitations in that regard, you could give it a try. Everything has its pros and cons; you should make your own judgment after weighing all the factors. The main thing to avoid is taking things at face value without considering different perspectives.
In simple terms, ultra-wide-angle, short-throw projectors—such as laser TVs—must use expensive ultra-wide-angle lenses and mirrors in order to get the image close to the screen. This does not conform to the principles of optimal optical design.
In order to block some of the ambient light, using a microstructured Fresnel screen comes at a high cost; the price of an 80-inch screen is roughly equivalent to that of a 65-inch LCD screen.
Another thing I really dislike is when projector manufacturers use the argument that diffused light is better for the eyes as a selling point. Come on, the light from the screen that our eyes see is actually direct light. Even if that light is diffused and then bounces off the ceiling, our eyes can’t see it. And it’s not like LCD TVs don’t emit diffused “direct light” either; doesn’t the ceiling get illuminated when the TV is turned on?
Moreover, if the projection screen does not exhibit diffuse reflection, it simply cannot form an image.
It’s precisely the heat spot (light spot) effect of high-gain screens that is often overlooked. A large amount of light reflected at a certain angle into the eyes can be truly uncomfortable.
